<TR BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=3><TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="LEFT">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=17&show_all=1"><font size=2>&lt;&lt;&lt;&nbsp;DEC&nbsp;17</font></a></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="CENTER"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl"><font size=2>HOME</font></a></TD><TD ALIGN="CENTER"><a class="addthis_button" href="http://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"><img src="http://s7.addthis.com/static/btn/v2/lg-share-en.gif" width="125" height="16" alt="Bookmark and Share" style="border:0"/></a><script type="text/javascript" src="http://s7.addthis.com/js/250/addthis_widget.js#pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"></script></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="RIGHT"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=19&show_all=1"><font size=2>DEC&nbsp;19&nbsp;&gt;&gt;&gt;</font></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR>
<TR HEIGHT=5><TD COLSPAN=3 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD>
<TD BACKGROUND="/black6.png">
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5><TR><TD>
	<TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=130 HEIGHT=130 SRC="chocs/choc_day_18.png" ALT="chocolate"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=190 SRC="globes/advent_globe_18.png" ALT="snowglobe"><table cellpadding=10 align="center" background="/black4.png" width=430><TR><TD><center><font size=6 color="#ffff00"><b><i>DRILLER</i></b></font><br><font size=3 color="red"><b><i>7 days to Christmas</i></b></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><p>
One of the exciting developments in the field of computing during the
80s was virtual reality. The idea of creating your own world which you
can then explore at your own leisure was such a step up from text
adventure games that you couldn't help but be transfixed by each new
demonstration which would pop up on TV programmes such as Tomorrow's
World.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/hhTVkSFC0A4&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/hhTVkSFC0A4&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>The Many Deaths In Knightmare</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Knightmare was a fantastic show for a guy like me - it was like playing in your own computer game back then. And for the watcher, the best part were the frequent deaths in this tough gameshow. As only one team completed a quest on average per series, there was quite a bit of suspense built up the further into a game a team reached. And then the inevitable happens. Enjoy... <b><i>(3:06)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hhTVkSFC0A4" target="hhTVkSFC0A4">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

<TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=150 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d18_1987_pre1.png" target="1987_pre1.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d18_1987_pre1_small.jpg" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=218></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>It really was as if Driller was just the name of a playable Freescape demo.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
I remember somehow blagging my way into a computer graphics exhibition
where the top floor was dedicated to giving all visitors their own
chance to wander through a simulated environment. So there I was,
standing in the middle of a large room wearing a rather large headset,
plus a joystick in my hand, making my way through a building with some
quite eccentric features, such as a room which was a fish tank, but
without water. That didn't seem to stop the virtual fish swimming
around me, presumably thinking the virtual equivalent of "oh look, a
castle!" The graphics were laughable compared to what you get today,
with everything being built with large 3D blocks and cylinders, and
little in the way of lighting effects and nothing in the way of
surface textures and patterns, but as it was the day in which I had my first
taste of a true virtual world, it was mind-blowing.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/UMqWizbXi6Q&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/UMqWizbXi6Q&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Knightmare, from an American's Point of View</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">A rather good, if sometimes inaccurate, review of the best kids show of the Eighties. Ignore the crappy bit at the start, it's worth sticking with. And don't miss <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sn2FwR4MQOk" target="sn2FwR4MQOk">part two</a> either! <b><i>(8:59)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UMqWizbXi6Q" target="UMqWizbXi6Q">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

The other form of alternative realities which was making waves in the
run-up to Christmas 1987 was a fantasy role-playing game on childrens'
television which used novel blue-screen techniques to produce a
challenging dungeon-based puzzle game. <i>Knightmare</i> placed the main
player, the "dungeoneer", in the thick of the action (actually a big
blue room the size of a double garage). The player would wear a helmet
<TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=199 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d18_1987_ad4.png" target="1987_ad4.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d18_1987_ad4_small.jpg" WIDTH=199 HEIGHT=291></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>Just a tad hypey, don't you think?!</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
that restricted his view to just being able to see what was below his
feet, maintaining the illusion that he was on some sort of quest, so
he would be guided by radio link by three other players in the studio
who viewed a screen which merged the computer graphics with the player
and the objects and characters he would interact with. This live
action "computer game" became a firm fixture in children's ITV
programming for eight series, and is still fondly remembered to this
day.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;With the influences of virtual reality floating around together with
the first attempts at filled 3D wireframe graphics on the Spectrum, it
was only natural that someone would take on the challenge of coming up
with a toolkit that could be used to form explorable 3D environments
on such humble hardware. Incentive began work on Freescape (TM) (yes,
the new technology was thought so ground-breaking that it deserved a
registered trademark!) in Autumn 1986, but it would be a full year
before the press would be told that something pretty special was about
to appear on the market.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/5LY9wTmurLc&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/5LY9wTmurLc&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Crash Driller Demo</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">This was on show in the PCW Show and shows off the Freescape technique. <b><i>(3:01)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5LY9wTmurLc" target="5LY9wTmurLc">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

Strangely enough, the first wave of hype was about Freescape itself -
<i>Driller</i> wasn't so much a game as a playable demonstration of the new
graphics technique. It was the cornerstone of Incentive's stall at
<TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=300 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d18_drillerdblad.jpg" target="drillerdblad.jpg"><IMG SRC="pngs/d18_drillerdblad_small.jpg" WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=217></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>Oh yes, the hype is strong with this one!</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
1987's PCW Show, and they printed many teaser adverts in a wide
selection of computer magazines in order to get the word out:
Freescape was the "new dimension", and you were missing out if you
didn't see it.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It needed the hype - whilst Freescape was an impressive technique, and
<i>Driller</i> was a large, challenging game, the price tag of &pound;15 wasn't
easy to swallow on its own! But even though the game had a slow pace
due to the complex mathematics behind the filled vector graphics,
later generations of the code in the sequels sped things up a bit
quite nicely. Whilst not entirely speedy, 1990's <i>Castle Master</i> using
Freescape+ and building the objects using a set of smaller objects
made the game feel considerably nippy.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The magazines loved it - admittedly the novelty factor had a large
part to play with the high ratings that <i>Driller</i> earned, but sales were
obviously healthy enough to encourage Incentive to refine the
Freescape engine and how they used it in four or five sequels,
finishing up with releasing a &pound;25 Freescape game designer in 1991. For
me it was purely something to read up on - it wasn't until <i>Castle
Master</i> when I actually played a Freescape game - but the technique was
impossible not to admire.
</TD></TR></TABLE><p>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
</TD><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD></TR>
